jpg|thumbnail|right|250px|[[Journey Beyond]] ''[[Indian Pacific]]'' from Perth to Sydney near Hawker Street, Bowden]]\n\nRail services around Adelaide are provided by a mixture of private and government-owned organisations.\n\nThe [[Department of Planning, Transport & Infrastructure]] (DPTI) owns and operates the suburban passenger rail network. This comprises six lines from [[Adelaide railway station]] on [[North Terrace]] in the CBD. The DPTI also owns and operates the [[Glenelg tram line]]. Adelaide's tram network is the only fully government owned and operated tram network in Australia.\n\nThe [[Australian Rail Track Corporation]] (ARTC), an agency of the [[Government of Australia|Federal Government]], owns standard gauge interstate lines heading north and south, together with the [[dual gauge]] freight-only branch from [[Dry Creek-Port Adelaide railway line|Dry Creek to Port Adelaide]] and [[Pelican Point (Adelaide)|Pelican Point]]. The ARTC lines bypass the city to the west and do not enter the CBD. The ARTC network extends from Adelaide towards Melbourne, Sydney, Perth and Darwin and is used by substantial interstate freight traffic.\n\nFreight trains are operated by a number of private operators, which have access agreements with rail network owners such as the ARTC. The largest of these is [[Pacific National]], which handles the majority of interstate traffic and has the largest locomotive fleet. Other logistics companies also operate freight trains to and from interstate destinations and within South Australia.\n\n[[One Rail Australia]] owns the remaining broad-gauge lines beyond the Adelaide suburban network. These are a handful of lines used mainly to move bulk grain and stone from the Barossa Valley and mid-north region of the state to the Port Adelaide area. \n\n[[Journey Beyond]] is a private company operating long-distance passenger trains on ARTCs standard gauge lines, and run from the [[Adelaide Parklands Terminal]], just west of the CBD. Journey Beyond\u2019s trains are the ''[[Indian Pacific]]'' to [[Central railway station, Sydney|Sydney]] and [[East Perth railway station|Perth]], ''[[The Ghan]]'' to [[Alice Springs railway station|Alice Springs]] and [[Darwin railway station|Darwin]], ''[[The Overland]]'' to [[Southern Cross railway station|Melbourne]] and the seasonal ''[[Great Southern (train)|Great Southern]]'' to [[Roma Street railway station|Brisbane]]. There have been no intrastate regional passenger services in South Australia since 1990.\n\nThere are presently two heritage railways in South Australia run by volunteers, but none of these are in the Adelaide area. The [[SteamRanger Heritage Railway]] is based at [[Mount Barker railway station|Mount Barker]] and runs services through to [[Victor Harbor railway station|Victor Harbor]]. The [[Pichi Richi Railway]] is considerably more distant from Adelaide, based at [[Quorn railway station|Quorn]], and runs services through to [[Port Augusta railway station|Port Augusta]].\n\n==History==\n===Early days===\nIn 1856, the first steam train ran between [[Adelaide]] and [[Port Adelaide]], stopping at [[Bowden railway station|Bowden]], [[Woodville railway station, Adelaide|Woodville]] and [[Alberton railway station, Adelaide|Alberton]].<ref>'''''The Adelaide, City and Port Railway''''' Callaghan, W.H. [[Australian Railway History]], April/May, 2005 pp123-138;143-149;182-195</ref> Soon after, a 40&nbsp;km line was built from the [[Gawler|Town of Gawler]] to [[Adelaide]] to cater for the agricultural and mining industries.\n\nThe South Line, through the [[Adelaide Hills]], opened to [[Aldgate, South Australia|Aldgate]], then [[Nairne, South Australia|Nairne]] in 1883, and extended to [[Bordertown, South Australia|Bordertown]] in 1886. The first through train between Adelaide and [[Melbourne, Victoria|Melbourne]] \u2013 ''The Intercolonial Express'' \u2013 ran on 19 January 1887, and was the first intercapital rail journey in Australia without changing trains at a [[break-of-gauge]] station.\n\nMost of the lines around Adelaide were built before 1900.\n\n===The Webb Era===\nDespite the earlier geographic expansion, by 1920 the infrastructure and rolling stock of [[South Australian Railways]] (SAR) had become run down, inadequate and outdated. Many of the operating practices, such as train control and signalling, were backward by the standards of the time.\n\nHowever the 1920s saw substantial and expensive improvements in most facets of the SAR\u2019s operations under the leadership of Railways Commissioner [[William Alfred Webb|William Webb]]. Webb was an American who had substantial operational experience with US railroads, and served as Commissioner between 1922 and 1930.\n\nDuring his reign, track, bridges, railway workshops, rolling stock and especially steam locomotives were all modernised and upgraded along essentially American lines. [[Adelaide railway station|Adelaide station]] was rebuilt with a handsome sandstone building as a showpiece of the city on [[North Terrace]]. The building still stands; the lower level remains as the railway station, but the upper levels have been converted into a casino.\n\nIn 1929, one of the original broad-gauge steam [[Holdfast Bay railway line|railways to the beach-side suburb of Glenelg]] was transferred to the [[Adelaide]] [[Municipal Tramways Trust]], electrified and converted to a tramway. The [[Glenelg tram]] line is still in operation.\n\n===SAR, STA and AN===\nFrom early colonial days up until 1978 the SAR had built and operated most of the railway system within the state.\n\nThe [[Commonwealth Railways]] (CR), owned by the Federal Government, also had a significant role in the northern part of SA, with lines from Port Augusta across the [[Nullarbor Plain]] to [[Kalgoorlie railway station|Kalgoorlie]], and to [[Marree railway station|Marree]] and [[Alice Springs railway station|Alice Springs]]. None of its lines came close to Adelaide.\n\nDuring the early 1970s the [[First Whitlam Ministry|Whitlam Federal Government]] proposed a strategy to nationalise and standardise the various state rail systems around Australia. South Australia and [[Tasmanian Government Railways|Tasmania]] were the only states to participate in this initiative and negotiations were long and drawn out. The result was that in March 1978 the SAR became defunct and South Australia\u2019s railways were split between Commonwealth and State Government ownership.\n\nA new Commonwealth Government organisation, [[Australian National Railways Commission]] (ANR), took over all the former SAR and CR track in South Australia outside the metropolitan area. Other rail facilities such as property and workshops were also transferred to ANR. ANR become Australian National (AN) as it refined its corporate identity.\n\nThe State Government retained ownership and control of tracks and trains in the Adelaide suburban area under the auspices of the [[State Transport Authority (South Australia)|State Transport Authority]] (STA). The STA had been created in 1974 to co-ordinate all public transport in South Australia.\n\nIn 1994 the STA was abolished and reformed as the government-owned corporate body [[TransAdelaide]] as a prelude to competitive tendering for operation of bus and rail services in metropolitan Adelaide. TransAdelaide subsequently lost all its bus services to private operators, but has retained the contracts to operate train and tram services.\n\nIn November 1997, AN was broken up and sold as part of a Federal Government privatisation agenda. Track, workshops, depots and passenger and freight operations were sold to various private organisations, which has led to today\u2019s operational structure described in an earlier section.\n\n==Future projects==\n===Gawler Line electrification===\n\nFollowing a decade of on-again, off-again talks,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-01-18/gawler-rail-line-disruptions-delayed-until-after-election/9340788 |title=Liberal MP's 'nana's nightie' remark on Gawler rail electrification steals the spotlight |date=18 January 2018 |website=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |access-date=7 July 2018}}</ref> electrification of the Gawler line was announced in 2018. The announcement only promised Stage 1 electrification as far as Salisbury with works to commence in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.railexpress.com.au/615m-gawler-electrification-deal-signed/ |title=$615m Gawler electrification deal signed |last=Probert |first=Oliver |date=22 January 2018 |website=Rail Express |access-date=7 July 2018}}</ref> A $220 million grant from the Federal Government also allowed for Stage 2 electrification for the remainder of the line to proceed. Works are expected to commence in 2018-19 to be completed by the end of 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langenberg |first=Adam |date=13 July 2018 |title=$615m Gawler electrification deal signed |url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/gawler-line-electrification-expected-to-be-completed-in-2020/news-story/6a228b49ae134aa83c3b96b1a0418d0f |work=The Advertiser |location=Adelaide |access-date=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Seaford Line extension to Aldinga===\nIn 2019, [[South Australian Housing Trust|Renewal SA]] delivered a Draft Structure Plan of a 94 hectare area of land in [[Aldinga, South Australia|Aldinga]] which is set to include a new school and a train station as an extension of the [[Seaford railway line]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.victorharbortimes.com.au/story/6188476/plan-for-land-revealed/|title=Development of Aldinga train station inches closer|website=Victor Harbour Times|date=29 May 2019|accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Tonsley Line extension to Flinders===\nAn extension of the [[Tonsley railway line]] to [[Flinders Medical Centre]] is under construction; major works commenced in July 2019 with expected completion in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wills |first=Daniel |date=29 April 2019 |title=Tonsley rail line extension to Flinders to be complete next year, price tag blows out to $125m |url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/tonsley-rail-line-extension-to-flinders-to-be-complete-next-year-price-tag-blows-out-to-125m/news-story/09e25037bc10022a98742829746fb646 |work=The Advertiser |location=Adelaide |access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Henson |first=Elizabeth |date=19 July 2019 |title=Construction work begins on $125m \u2018Flinders Link\u2019, a 650m extension of old Tonsley line |url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/construction-work-begins-on-125m-flinders-link-a-650m-extension-of-old-tonsley-line/news-story/a94ab3be5540f3dc7f0fda381f1b3153 |work=The Advertiser |location=Adelaide |access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Underground city centre link===\nInfrastructure SA intends to complete electrification of the Gawler line, and analyse feasibility of an underground rail link in the CBD between the northern and southern train lines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://infrastructure.sa.gov.au/project-pipeline|title= Project Pipeline - Infrastructure SA|accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Railway lines==\n===Main passenger lines===\nAdelaide has six broad gauge railway lines that provide passenger services for the suburban network:\n\n{{AdelaideMetroBus | bgcolour=#{{Adelaide Metro color|Belair}} | ftcolour=#ffffff | rte=[[Belair railway line|<span style=\"color:white;\">Belair Line</span>]]}} (21.5&nbsp;km):\n*[[Adelaide railway station|Adelaide]] to [[Bridgewater railway station, Adelaide|Bridgewater]] built in 1883 \u2013 37.66&nbsp;km\n*[[Belair railway station|Belair]] to [[Bridgewater railway station, Adelaide|Bridgewater]] closed 1987\n**Adelaide to Melbourne via Belair and Bridgewater was converted to standard gauge in 1995, leaving one broad-gauge track from Goodwood to Belair\n\n{{AdelaideMetroBus | bgcolour=#{{Adelaide Metro color|Gawler}} | ftcolour=#ffffff | rte=[[Gawler railway line|<span style=\"color:white;\">Gawler Line</span>]]}} (42.2&nbsp;km):\n*[[Adelaide railway station|Adelaide]] to [[Gawler railway station|Gawler]] built in 1857\n*Gawler to [[Gawler Central railway station|Gawler Central]] built in 1911\n\n{{AdelaideMetroBus | bgcolour=#{{Adelaide Metro color|Grange}} | ftcolour=#ffffff | rte=[[Grange railway line|<span style=\"color:white;\">Grange Line</span>]]}} (5.5&nbsp;km):\n*[[Woodville railway station, Adelaide|Woodville]] to [[Grange railway station|Grange]] built in 1882 \u2013 13&nbsp;km\n*Grange to [[Henley Beach railway station|Henley Beach]] built in 1894, closed and dismantled 1957\n\n{{AdelaideMetroBus | bgcolour=#{{Adelaide Metro color|Outer Harbor}} | ftcolour=#ffffff | rte=[[Outer Harbor railway line|<span style=\"color:white;\">Outer Harbor Line</span>]]}} (21.9&nbsp;km):\n*[[Adelaide railway station|Adelaide]] to [[Port Dock railway station|Port Dock]] built in 1856 \u2013 11.7&nbsp;km\n*[[Port Adelaide railway station|Port Adelaide]] to [[Outer Harbor railway station|Outer Harbor]] built in 1908 \u2013 10.2&nbsp;km\n\n{{AdelaideMetroBus | bgcolour=#{{Adelaide Metro color|Seaford}} | ftcolour=#ffffff | rte=[[Seaford railway line|<span style=\"color:white;\">Seaford Line</span>]]}} (36.0&nbsp;km):\n*[[Goodwood railway station|Goodwood]] to [[Marino railway station, Adelaide|Marino]] built in 1913 \u2013 18.3&nbsp;km\n*Marino to [[Hallett Cove railway station|Hallett Cove]] built in 1915 \u2013 3.1&nbsp;km\n*[[Lonsdale railway station|Lonsdale]] to [[Christie Downs railway station|Christie Downs]] built in 1976 \u2013 2.2&nbsp;km\n*Christie Downs to [[Noarlunga Centre Interchange|Noarlunga Centre]] built in 1978 \u2013 1.3&nbsp;km\n*Noarlunga Centre to [[Seaford railway station, Adelaide|Seaford]] opened in February 2014 \u2013 5.8&nbsp;km\n\n{{AdelaideMetroBus | bgcolour=#{{Adelaide Metro color|Tonsley}} | ftcolour=#ffffff | rte=[[Tonsley railway line|<span style=\"color:white;\">Tonsley Line</span>]]}} (3.9&nbsp;km):\n*[[Woodlands Park railway station|Woodlands Park]] to [[Tonsley railway station|Tonsley]] built in 1966 \u2013 3.9&nbsp;km\n*Tonsley to Flinders under construction, to open in 2020 \u2013 650&nbsp;m\n\n===Closed lines===\n[[Image:willunga-marino railtrail in reynella.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The [[Coast to Vines Rail Trail]], built on the route of the former Willunga line.]]\n{{main|List of closed railway stations in South Australia}}\nAdelaide's passenger rail network has decreased in size since the 1950s, with the closure of several lines and branches, including:\n\n*'''[[Dry Creek-Port Adelaide railway line|Dry Creek\u2013Port Adelaide line]]''': built in 1868 (last passenger service in 1988)\n*'''[[Finsbury railway line|Finsbury line]]''': [[Woodville railway station, Adelaide|Woodville]] to Finsbury Stores built in 1940 (closed in 1978)\n*'''[[Northfield railway line|Northfield line]]''': [[Adelaide railway station|Adelaide]] to [[Northfield railway station|Northfield]] built in 1857 (closed in 1987)\n*'''[[Penfield railway line|Penfield line]]''': [[Salisbury railway station, Adelaide|Salisbury]] to [[Penfield 3 railway station|Penfield 3]] built in 1941 (closed and dismantled in 1991)\n*'''[[Semaphore railway line|Semaphore line]]''': [[Port Adelaide]] to Semaphore built in 1878 (closed and dismantled in 1978)\n*'''[[Willunga railway line|Willunga line]]''': [[Hallett Cove railway station|Hallett Cove]] to [[Willunga, South Australia|Willunga]] built in 1915 (closed in 1969; now the [[Coast to Vines Rail Trail]])\n\n==Current rolling stock==\n*30 [[3000 class railcar]]s built by [[Commonwealth Engineering]] and [[Clyde Engineering]], 1988-1996\n*40 3100 class railcars built by [[Commonwealth Engineering]] and [[Clyde Engineering]], 1988-1996\n*22 [[Adelaide Metro A-City Class 4000|A-City Class 4000]] Electric Multiple Units built by [[Bombardier Transportation]]\n\n==See also==\n\n===Adelaide Railway===\n*[[List of Adelaide railway stations]]\n*[[List of closed Adelaide railway stations]]\n*[[List of public transport routes in Adelaide]]\n*[[Redhen railcar]]\n*[[2000 class railcar]]\n*[[Glenelg Tram]]\n*[[3000 class railcar]]\n\n===Adelaide===\n*[[Transport in Adelaide]]\n*[[Adelaide Metro]]\n*[[Trams in Adelaide]]\n\n===South Australia===\n*[[Rail transport in South Australia]]\n* [[Transport in South Australia]]\n\n===Australia===\n*[[Rail transport in Australia]]\n*[[Transport in Australia]]\n\n===Worldwide===\n*[[List of suburban and commuter rail systems]]\n\n==References and notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sa.gov.au South Australia Central]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050205211219/http://www.opt.dtup.sa.gov.au/ Office of Public Transport]\n*[http://www.adelaidemetro.com.au/ Adelaide Metro]\n*[http://www.natrailmuseum.org.au/ National Railway Museum, Port Adelaide]\n*[http://www.steamranger.org.au/ SteamRanger]\n*[http://www.sa-trackandsignal.net/ SA railway track and signalling]\n\n{{Adelaide public transport}}\n{{Australian rail}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Regional rail in Australia]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in South Australia]]\n[[Category:5 ft 3 in gauge railways in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "date format audit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Railways_in_Adelaide"}
{"title_page": "Paul Schaub", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n|                name = Paul Schaub\n|               image =\n|            fullname = Paul Schaub\n|          birth_date = 1907\n|         birth_place = Switzerland\n|          death_date = unknown\n|         death_place = \n|              height = \n|            position = [[Midfielder (football)|Midfielder]]\n|         currentclub = \n|          clubnumber = \n|         youthyears1 = \n|         youthclubs1 = \n|              years1 = 1926\u20131937\n|              clubs1 = [[FC Basel|Basel]]\n|               caps1 = 179\n|              goals1 = 9\n|              years2 = 1938\u20131939\n|              clubs2 = [[FC Kreuzlingen|Kreuzlingen]]\n|               caps2 = \n|              goals2 =\n|      nationalyears1 = 1934 \n|       nationalteam1 = [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] \n|       nationalcaps1 = 1\n|      nationalgoals1 = 0\n|       manageryears1 = \n|       managerclubs1 = \n|            pcupdate = \n|            ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Paul Schaub''' (born 1907; date of death unknown) was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[football (soccer)|footballer]] who played for [[FC Basel]] and [[FC Kreuzlingen]]. He also played one game for [[Switzerland national football team|Swiss national team]]. He played mainly in the position of [[Midfielder (football)|midfielder]]. \n\nSchaub joined Basel's first team in advance of their [[1926\u201327 FC Basel season|1926\u201327 season]]. After playing just one test match, he played his domestic league debut for the club in the home game at the [[Landhof]] on 14 May 1927 as Basel won 1\u20130 against local rivals [[FC Concordia Basel|Concordia Basel]].<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-concordia 1926/27\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=29434 | title = FC Basel - FC Concordia Basel 1:0 (1:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> He scored his first goal for his club on 12 May 1929 in the away game against [[FC Aarau|Aarau]]. In fact Schaub scored two goals in that game, as the two teams played a 2\u20132 draw.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fca-fcb 1928/29\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=29368 | title = FC Aarau - FC Basel 2:2 (0:1) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nBetween the years 1926 and 1937 Schaub played a total of 283 games for Basel, scoring a total of 11 goals. 179 of these games were in the [[Swiss Super League|Swiss Serie A/Nationalliga]], 26 in the [[Swiss Cup]] and 77 were friendly games. He scored 9 goals in the domestic league, the other two were scored during the test games.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-schaun\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/spieler?command=detail&id=8973 | title = Paul Schaub | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2018-11-16}}</ref> He was a member of the Basel team that won the Swiss Cup in the [[1932\u201333 FC Basel season|1932\u201333 season]]. The final was played in the [[Hardturm]] stadium against [[Grasshopper Club Z\u00fcrich|Grasshopper Club]]. Basel won 4\u20133 and achieved the club's first ever national title.<ref name=\"fussball-schweiz\">{{cite web | first = | last = Fussball-Schweiz | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://fussball-schweiz.ch/schweizer-cup/finals-1926-1939/index.html | title = Schweizer Cup Finals 1926-1939 | format = | work = | publisher = Fussball-Schweiz | accessdate = 2018-11-16}}</ref> He later played one season for Kreuzlingen and then ended his active football career.\n\nSchaub was called up for the [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] for the first time in 1932. He played one match for his country and this was on 14 October 1934 in the [[Charmilles Stadium]], [[Geneva]], against [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] as the two teams drew 2\u20132.<ref name=\"eu-football-ch-czech-1934\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=5773 | title = Switzerland - Czechoslovakia 2:2 | format = | work = | publisher = eu-football-info | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[Swiss Cup]] winner: 1932\u201333\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}} \n\n==Sources==\n* Rotblau: Jahrbuch Saison 2017/2018. Publisher: FC Basel Marketing AG. {{ISBN|978-3-7245-2189-1}}\n* Die ersten 125 Jahre. Publisher: Josef Zindel im Friedrich Reinhardt Verlag, Basel. {{ISBN|978-3-7245-2305-5}}\n* [https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/home Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\" Homepage]\n\n{{Authority control}} \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schaub, Paul }}\n\n[[Category:FC Basel players]]\n[[Category:Swiss footballers]]\n[[Category:Switzerland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|                name = Paul Schaub\n|               image =\n|            fullname = Paul Schaub\n|          birth_date = 1907\n|         birth_place = Switzerland\n|          death_date = unknown\n|         death_place = \n|              height = \n|            position = [[Midfielder (football)|Midfielder]]\n|         currentclub = \n|          clubnumber = \n|         youthyears1 = \n|         youthclubs1 = \n|              years1 = 1926\u20131937\n|              clubs1 = [[FC Basel|Basel]]\n|               caps1 = 179\n|              goals1 = 9\n|              years2 = 1938\u20131939\n|              clubs2 = [[FC Kreuzlingen|Kreuzlingen]]\n|               caps2 = \n|              goals2 =\n|      nationalyears1 = 1932\u20131934 \n|       nationalteam1 = [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] \n|       nationalcaps1 = 1\n|      nationalgoals1 = 0\n|       manageryears1 = \n|       managerclubs1 = \n|            pcupdate = \n|            ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Paul Schaub''' (born in 1907; date of death unknown) was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[football (soccer)|footballer]] who played for [[FC Basel]] and [[FC Kreuzlingen]]. He also played one game for [[Switzerland national football team|Swiss national team]]. He played mainly in the position of [[Midfielder (football)|midfielder]]. \n\nSchaub joined Basel's first team in advance of their [[1926\u201327 FC Basel season|1926\u201327 season]]. After playing just one test match, he played his domestic league debut for the club in the home game at the [[Landhof]] on 14 May 1927 as Basel won 1\u20130 against local rivals [[FC Concordia Basel|Concordia Basel]].<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-concordia 1926/27\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=29434 | title = FC Basel - FC Concordia Basel 1:0 (1:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> He scored his first goal for his club on 12 May 1929 in the away game against [[FC Aarau|Aarau]]. In fact Schaub scored two goals in that game, as the two teams played a 2\u20132 draw.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fca-fcb 1928/29\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=29368 | title = FC Aarau - FC Basel 2:2 (0:1) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nBetween the years 1926 and 1937 Schaub played a total of 283 games for Basel, scoring a total of 11 goals. 179 of these games were in the [[Swiss Super League|Swiss Serie A/Nationalliga]], 26 in the [[Swiss Cup]] and 77 were friendly games. He scored 9 goals in the domestic league, the other two were scored during the test games.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-schaun\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/spieler?command=detail&id=8973 | title = Paul Schaub | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2018-11-16}}</ref> He was a member of the Basel team that won the Swiss Cup in the [[1932\u201333 FC Basel season|1932\u201333 season]]. The final was played in the [[Hardturm]] stadium against [[Grasshopper Club Z\u00fcrich|Grasshopper Club]]. Basel won 4\u20133 and achieved the club's first ever national title.<ref name=\"fussball-schweiz\">{{cite web | first = | last = Fussball-Schweiz | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://fussball-schweiz.ch/schweizer-cup/finals-1926-1939/index.html | title = Schweizer Cup Finals 1926-1939 | format = | work = | publisher = Fussball-Schweiz | accessdate = 2018-11-16}}</ref> He later played one season for Kreuzlingen and then ended his active football career.\n\nSchaub was called up for the [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] for the first time in 1932. He played one match for his country and this was on 14 October 1934 in the [[Charmilles Stadium]], [[Geneva]], against [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] as the two teams drew 2\u20132.<ref name=\"eu-football-ch-czech-1934\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=5773 | title = Switzerland - Czechoslovakia 2:2 | format = | work = | publisher = eu-football-info | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[Swiss Cup]] winner: 1932\u201333\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}} \n\n==Sources==\n* Rotblau: Jahrbuch Saison 2017/2018. Publisher: FC Basel Marketing AG. {{ISBN|978-3-7245-2189-1}}\n* Die ersten 125 Jahre. Publisher: Josef Zindel im Friedrich Reinhardt Verlag, Basel. {{I