{"title_page": "Howie Weinberg", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Howie Weinberg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = [[United States]]\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[Americans|American]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Audio mastering engineer\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Howie Weinberg''' is an [[United States|American]] [[Grammy Award|9 X Grammy Award-Winning]] [[Audio mastering|mastering]] engineer with 23 [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] [[Grammy nominated|nominations.]] He has over 200 [[Music recording certification|Gold]] and [[Music recording certification|Platinum]] records.  He has over 19 K [[Credit (creative arts)|credits]] according to [[AllMusic]].<ref>[http://www.star-ecentral.com/news/story.asp?file=/2007/11/5/music/19283949&sec=music platinum records]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/howie-weinberg-mn0000828374/credits|title=Howie Weinberg {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> And, holds 4 [[TEC Awards]], 2 [[Juno Award|Juno Awards]] and 1 [[Mercury Prize]] Award. \n\n== Career ==\nIn 2011 he moved to [[Los Angeles]] and opened Howie Weinberg Mastering located in [[Laurel Canyon, Los Angeles|Laurel Canyon]] after working at [[Masterdisk]], [[New York City]], since 1979.       \n\nWeinberg [[Mastering (audio)|mastered]] several of [[Bill Laswell|Bill Laswell's]] releases, such as [[Herbie Hancock]]'s [[Grammy Award]] winning album ''[[Future Shock (Herbie Hancock album)|Future Shock]]'' which included the  hit single \"[[Rockit (song)|Rockit]] which was [[Grammy nominated]] 3 X and won a [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Instrumental Performance]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/herbie-hancock|title=Herbie Hancock|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> in 1983.       \n\nHe also [[Mastering (audio)|mastered]] ''[[Rhythm Killers]]'' by [[Sly and Robbie]], ''[[Brain Drain (album)|Brain Drain]]'' by the [[Ramones]], [[Material (band)|Material]]'s ''[[Memory Serves]]'' and [[Buckethead]]'s debut album ''[[Bucketheadland]]''.       \n\nOther notable works include the [[Beastie Boys]]' ''[[Licensed to Ill]]''  which was certified [[RIAA certification|Diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] in 2015 for shipping over ten million copies in the United States.      \n\nHowie Weinberg [[mastered]] the multi-platinum 1991 studio album ''[[Nevermind]]'' by [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] which was [[Grammy nominated]] in 1991 for  [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Music Album]] and was then [[Grammy nominated|2 X Grammy nominated]] the following year of 1992 for its single, [[Smells Like Teen Spirit]] that was [[Grammy nominated|nominated]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance|Best Hard Rock Performance]] and [[Best Rock Song|Best Rock Song.]] The [[album]] was later inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/nirvana|title=Nirvana|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>  \n\nHis mastering work on [[Rush (band)|Rush]]'s ''[[Vapor Trails]]'' drew some criticism for its [[Loudness war|extremely compressed dynamics]] by the band in 2002 which was an [[audio]] trend during the time.  The [[album]], nevertheless, went [[Music recording certification|Gold]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Vapor Trails|date=2019-11-02|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Vapor_Trails&oldid=924168852|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> \n\nHowie Weinberg currently has over 200 [[Gold Record|Gold & Platinum Records]].  He works with [[Celebrity|celebrities]], [[record label]]<nowiki/>s and [[Independent Artists (company)|independent artists.]]  \n\n<blockquote>Once [[Andy Wallace (producer)|Andy Wallace]] had finished his mix of ''Nevermind'', the master tapes were forwarded to Howie Weinberg at Masterdisk Studios in New York City. \"I'm sort of a goal tender in the creative process,\" says Howie Weinberg at Masterdisk Studios in New York. \"I'm the last stop to make it better before pressing.\"</blockquote>\n\nWeinberg also worked with [[Miley Cyrus]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]], [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Van Halen]], [[Tom Waits]], [[The Mars Volta]], [[Billy Corgan]], [[Spoon (band)|Spoon]], [[Public Enemy (band)|Public Enemy]], [[Yoko Ono]], [[PJ Harvey]], [[Rammstein]], [[Thirty Seconds to Mars]], [[Metallica]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metallica.com/store/music/cds/13709/master-of-puppets-remastered-cd|title=Master of Puppets (Remastered) - CD - Metallica|website=Metallica|access-date=2017-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830200613/https://www.metallica.com/store/music/cds/13709/master-of-puppets-remastered-cd|archive-date=2017-08-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Aerosmith]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Power|first=Martin|author2=Chris Charlesworth|title=The Complete Guide to the Music of Aerosmith|publisher=Omnibus Press|year=1997|pages=73|isbn=978-0-7119-5598-1}}</ref> 30Aut6<ref>[https://soundcloud.com/30aut6/last-night Soundcloud.com]</ref> and [[The White Stripes]]. [[Dimebag Darrell]] of [[Pantera]] fame is quoted as saying:\n\n<blockquote>When you get to mastering you've got to find the magic mix that works once it goes through all the compression and EQing. We worked with Howie Weinberg and he's a fantabulous motherfucker.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kitts|first=Jeff|title=Guitar World Presents Nu-Metal|publisher=Hal Leonard Publishing Corporation|year=2002|pages=[https://archive.org/details/guitarworldprese00kitt/page/35 35]|isbn=978-0-634-03287-5|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/guitarworldprese00kitt/page/35}}</ref>\n<br /></blockquote>\n\nIn 1991 [[Soundgarden]]'s [[Badmotorfinger]] was [[Grammy nominated]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/soundgarden|title=Soundgarden|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>and was [[Mastering (audio)|mastered]] by Howie Weinberg.\n\nIn 1995 [[The Red Hot Chili Peppers (album)|The Red Hot Chili Peppers album]] [[Grammy nominated|Blood Sugar Sex Magik]] was [[Grammy nominated]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance|Best Hard Rock Performance]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/red-hot-chili-peppers|title=Red Hot Chili Peppers|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The [[album]] was masted by him.\n\nIn 1997 he won a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]] [[The Smashing Pumpkins]]'s [[The End Is the Beginning Is the End]] which won a [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/videos/smashing-pumpkins-win-best-hard-rock-performance|title=Smashing Pumpkins Win Best Hard Rock Performance|date=2010-02-26|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997 [[U2]]'s [[Pop (U2 album)|Pop]] was [[Grammy nominated]] and Weinberg mastered the [[album]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/u2|title=U2|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2001 he received a [[Mercury Prize]] for mastering [[PJ Harvey]]'s 2 X [[Grammy nominated]] album [[Stories from the City, Stories from the Sea]].  It was [[Grammy nominated]] for  [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Album|Best Rock Album]] and [[Best Female Rock Vocal Performance]] for the single \"[[This Is Love (PJ Harvey song)|This Is Love]]\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/pj-harvey|title=PJ Harvey|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\u00a0  \n\nIn 2003 his work for [[Beastie Boys]] [[Licensed to Ill]] was ranked number 217 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's list of [[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|the 500 greatest albums of all time]].  \n\nIn 2003 he won a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] for mastering [[Sheryl Crow]]'s ''[[Sheryl Crow|C'mon, C'mon]]'' which was released in 2002, spawning the hit single \"[[Soak Up the Sun]]\". The second single, \"Steve McQueen\", which won [[Best Female Rock Vocal Performance]]. The album was 4 X [[Grammy nominated]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sheryl-crow|title=Sheryl Crow|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\nIn 2004 ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranking [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana's]]  [[Nevermind]] number 27 on their list of the [[Rolling Stone's 100 Greatest Artists of All Time|100 Greatest Artists of All Time]] and again, at number 30 on their updated list in 2011.  \n\nIn 2006 he won a [[Latin Grammy Award|Latin Grammy]] for [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]] [[Ah\u00ed vamos]] which won for [[Latin Grammy Award|Best Rock Solo Vocal]]. \n\nIn 2008 he won a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] for  [[Grammy Award|mastering]]  [[Daft Punk]]'s [[Alive 2007]] which won [[Best Electronic/Dance Album]] in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/daft-punk|title=Daft Punk|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\nHe appeared at the 2009 [[South by Southwest|SXSW]] on the Panel: Producers On Making Classic Records.<ref>[http://www.sxsw.com/music/talks/schedule/?action=bio&id=16515 SXSW]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> \n\nIn January 2011, he left Masterdisk to set up his own mastering company in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonicscoop.com/2011/01/08/bidding-farewell-to-howie-weinberg-masterdisk-promotes-matt-agoglia-to-senior-mastering-engineer/|publisher=SonicScoop|title=Bidding Farewell to Howie Weinberg, Masterdisk Promotes Matt Agoglia to Senior Mastering Engineer|date=January 8, 2011|author=Janice Brown|accessdate=2011-02-11}}</ref>.  \n\nIn 2013 he was [[Grammy nominated]] for [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]] [[Fiona Apple]]'s [[The Idler Wheel...]] which was [[Grammy nominated]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Music Album.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/fiona-apple|title=Fiona Apple|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>  \n\nin 2017 his work from [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana's]], [[Smells Like Teen Spirit]] , was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/nirvana|title=Nirvana|date=2019-11-19|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2019 he won a [[Latin Grammy Award records|Latin Grammy Award]]  for [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]] [[Mon Laferte]]'s [[Norma (album)|Norma]]  won a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] for [[Best Alternative Music Album]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/mon-laferte-wins-best-alternative-album-norma-2019-latin-grammys|title=Mon Laferte Wins Latin GRAMMY Best Alt. Album|date=2019-11-14|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2020 he won [[Grammy Award|3 Grammy's]] for [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]] [[Gary Clark Jr.]]'s album [[This Land (Gary Clark Jr. album)]] which won 3 [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]] and had 4 [[Grammy nominated|Grammy nominations.]] The album won [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Blues Album|Best Contemporary Blues Album]], [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance]], [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song]], and was [[Grammy nominated]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/gary-clark-jr|title=Gary Clark, Jr.|date=2020-02-05|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>   \n\n== Award ==\nHe has been nominated for the Mix Foundation's [[TEC Awards|Technical Excellence & Creativity award]] for mastering engineer in 1997,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/1997.html|title=1997 TEC Awards winners|accessdate=2009-05-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120914065954/http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/1997.html|archivedate=2012-09-14}}</ref> was part of two of the winners in 2003 (best track with [[Sheryl Crow]]'s \"[[Soak Up the Sun]]\"; best record for Sheryl Crow's ''[[C'mon, C'mon]]''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/03winners.html|title=2003 WINNERS FOR OUTSTANDING TECHNICAL ACHIEVEMENT|accessdate=2009-05-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081027154821/http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/03winners.html|archivedate=2008-10-27}}</ref> and was part of the winners for best track in 2006 with [[Gorillaz]]' \"[[Feel Good Inc.|Feel Good Inc]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/06winners.html|title=2006 TEC Awards Winners|accessdate=2009-05-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606090908/http://mixfoundation.org/tec/06winners.html|archivedate=2009-06-06}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nHowie Weinberg married Rachel Felder, the director of artists and repertory at [[Columbia Records]] in July 1999.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/18/style/weddings-rachel-felder-howie-weinberg.html?sec=&spon=| title=WEDDINGS; Rachel Felder, Howie Weinberg| work=The New York Times| date=July 18, 1999}}</ref> The couple separated in 2009 and divorced soon after.\n\n==Partial discography==\nIf not stated otherwise, Howie Weinberg received credits for mastering and listed in alphabetical order:\n\n* [[...And You Will Know Us by the Trail of Dead]] - ''[[Source Tags & Codes]]'' (2002)\n* [[13 Engines]] - ''Perpetual Motion Machine'' (1993)\n* [[24-7 Spyz]] - ''[[Heavy Metal Soul by the Pound]]'' (1996)\n* [[2nd II None]] - [[2nd II None (album)|''2nd II None'']] (1991)\n* [[3 Doors Down]] - ''[[Seventeen Days]]'' (2005)\n* [[3 Colours Red]] - ''[[The Union of Souls]]'' (2004)\n* [[3rd Bass]] - ''[[The Cactus Album]]'' (1989), ''[[Derelicts of Dialect]]'' (1991)\n* [[54-40 (band)|54-40]] - ''[[Since When]]'' (1998)\n* [[7horse]] - ''Songs for a Voodoo Wedding'' (2014); ''Livin in a Bitch of a World'' (2016)\n* [[A Dozen Furies]] - ''[[A Concept from Fire]]'' (2005)\n* [[A Giant Dog]] - ''Pile'' (2016)\n* [[A Perfect Murder (band)|A Perfect Murder]] - [[Unbroken (A Perfect Murder album)|''Unbroken'']] (2004); ''[[Strength Through Vengeance]]'' (2005)\n* [[A (band)|A]] - [['A' vs. Monkey Kong|''<nowiki/>'A' vs. Monkey Kong'']] (2000)\n* [[Abiodun Oyewole]] - ''25 Years'' (1996)\n* [[Acid Test (band)|Acid Test]] - ''Drop'' (1993)\n* [[Active Child]] - ''You Are All I See'' (2011); ''Rapor'' (2013)\n* [[Adele Bertei]] - ''Little Lives'' (1988)\n* [[Aerosmith]] - ''[[Done with Mirrors]]'' (1985)\n* [[After the Fall (band)|After the Fall]] - ''[[Always Forever Now]]'' (2005)\n* [[Alabama 3]] - ''[[Exile on Coldharbour Lane]]'' (1997)\n* [[Aleks Syntek]] - ''[[89\u201399]]'' (2000)\n* [[Alice Cooper]] - [[The Last Temptation (Alice Cooper album)|''The Last Temptation'']] (1994)\n* [[Alien Crime Syndicate]] - ''[[Dust to Dirt]]'' (2000); ''[[From the Word Go]]'' (2000); ''[[Ten Songs in the Key of Betrayal]]'' (2004)\n* [[All Hail the Yeti]] - ''All Hail the Yeti'' (2012)\n* [[The Almighty (band)|The Almighty]] - ''[[Psycho-Narco]]'' (2001